..TEXT:
Gibbon, ch. L., says: "At the conclusion of the
Life of Mahomet, it may perhaps be expected that I should balance
his faults and virtues, that I should decide whether the title of
enthusiast or impostor more properly belongs to that
extraordinary man.  Had I been intimately conversant with the son
of Abdallah, the task would still be difficult, and the success
uncertain; at the distance of twelve centuries, I darkly
contemplate his shade through a cloud of religious incense; and
could I truly delineate the portrait of an hour, the fleeting
resemblance would not equally apply to the solitary of Mount
Hera, to the preacher of Mecca, and to the conqueror of
Arabia.....  From enthusiasm to imposture the step is perilous
and slippery; the daemon of Socrates affords a memorable
instance how a wise man may deceive himself, how a good man may
deceive others, how the conscience may slumber in a mixed and
middle state between self-illusion and voluntary fraud."
..TEXT:
Of Ali, the son-in-law and faithful follower of Mahomet,
he goes on to say: "He united the qualifications of a poet, a
soldier, and a saint; his wisdom still breathes in a collection
of moral and religious sayings; and every antagonist, in the
combats of the tongue or of the sword, was subdued by his
eloquence and valor.  From the first hour of his mission to the
last rites of his funeral, the apostle was never forsaken by a
generous friend, whom he delighted to name his brother, his
vice-gerent, and the faithful Aaron of a second Moses."
